ucestershire, England","Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales","Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1309–1361":"1309–1361","1300–1348":"1300–1348","1320–1377":"1320–1377","1332–1399":"1332–1399","1329–1363":"1329–1363","1332–1372":"1332–1372","1292–1335":"1292–1335","1290–Female":"1290–Overleden","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","1372":"1372","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1348":"1348","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1399":"1399","1377":"1377","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1309":"1309","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Rhaglan, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Cirencester, Gloucestershire, England":"Cirencester, Gloucestershire, England","Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales","Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1309–1361":"1309–1361","1300–1348":"1300–1348","1320–1377":"1320–1377","1332–1399":"1332–1399","1329–1363":"1329–1363","1332–1372":"1332–1372","1292–1335":"1292–1335","1290–Female":"1290–Deceased","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","1372":"1372","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1348":"1348","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1399":"1399","1377":"1377","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1309":"1309","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Rhaglan, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","England":"England","Cirencester, Gloucestershire, England":"Cirencester, Gloucestershire, England","Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales","Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Blewett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>bleuet</i>, <i>blouet</i> ‘bluish’, a diminutive of <i>bleu</i> ‘blue’, more specifically ‘pale, pallid, wan’, or ‘fair-haired, golden-haired’. Compare   Blew  ,   Blewitt  , and   Bluett  .","History: The Norman Ralph Bloet is mentioned in Domesday Book (1086) as lord of the manor of Hinton in Hampshire, recorded in 1246 as <i>Henton Bluet</i> (modern Hinton Blewett). From the late 12th century onward many Anglo-Norman knights acquired estates in Ireland. Ralph's presumed descendants, Thomas and Ralph Bluet, held lands in counties Cork and Limerick before and after 1254, and are ancestors of the modern Irish families named Bluett, Blewett, and Blewitt. In 1850, following the Irish Potato Famine in Ireland (1845–49), Patrick Blewitt, a son of Edward Blewitt of Ballina, County Mayo, migrated to North America, his whole family joining him in 1851 to settle in Scranton PA. Joe Biden (see   Biden  ), the 46th president of the US, is Edward's great-great-great grandson."],"variants":[{"name":"Blewitt","meanings":["English: variant of   Blewett  ."]},{"name":"Bluett","meanings":["English (Cornwall): variant of   Blewett  ."]},{"name":"Blew","meanings":["Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Blau   ‘blue’. Compare   Blue  .","English: from Middle English <i>blew(e)</i>, a variant of <i>bleu</i> ‘blue’ (Old French <i>bleu</i>), ‘pale, pallid, wan’ (of complexion), or ‘fair, golden’ (of hair). Compare   Blewett  ."]},{"name":"Biden","meanings":["English (Hampshire and Surrey): habitational name, probably from Baydon (Wiltshire). The placename may have meant ‘hill associated with a woman named Bēage’ (a personal name derived from Old English <i>bēag</i> ‘ring, bracelet, torque’ + Old English <i>dūn</i>). The surname is pronounced /'baidən/.","History: The surname <i>Biden</i> has a long history in East Meon (Hampshire), recorded there from 1327 until at least the 1840s. — Joe Biden, the 46th president of the US, is of Irish, English, and French descent. His mother’s Jean (Catherine Eugenia) Finnegan entire family tree traces back to Ireland, with some of the ancestors named Blewitt (see   Blewett  )."]},{"name":"Bluitt","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Blewett  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":6,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":19,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":28,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Ralph de Blewett was born in 1309, in Cirencester, Gloucestershire, England, his father, Sir Ralph de Blewett, was 17 and his mother, Amicia Picard, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Margery Poyntz. He died in 1361, in Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1309–1361":"1309–1361","1300–1348":"1300–1348","1320–1377":"1320–1377","1332–1399":"1332–1399","1329–1363":"1329–1363","1332–1372":"1332–1372","1292–1335":"1292–1335","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","1372":"1372","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1348":"1348","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1399":"1399","1377":"1377","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1309":"1309","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Rhaglan, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","England":"England","Cirencester, Gloucestershire, England":"Cirencester, Gloucestershire, England","Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales","Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1309–1361":"1309–1361","1300–1348":"1300–1348","1320–1377":"1320–1377","1332–1399":"1332–1399","1329–1363":"1329–1363","1332–1372":"1332–1372","1292–1335":"1292–1335","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","1372":"1372","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1348":"1348","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1335":"133